AB  - HE STUDY, conducted in the semi-arid upper Cheliff perimeter of Khemis-Miliana, Algeria, over two growing seasons (2022-2023 and 2023-2024), evaluated the impact of supplemental irrigation on wheat yield, straw biomass, and water productivity under drought conditions. The experimental design used was a randomized complete block with tree replicates. Each replicate was divided into four levels representing the different water regimes of treatment applied. For these experiments, two wheat varieties commonly cultivated by Algerian farmers were chosen: Oued El Bared (Triticum turgidum L. subsp. durum (Desf) Husn) for the first experiment and Arz (Triticum aestivum L.) for the second. In the 2022-2023 season, four applications per crop stage resulted in increases of 86 % for grain yields and 88 % for dry straw with 1500 m3 ha-1 about rainfed conditions. In the following season (2023-2024), the increases were 82 % for grain yields and 72 % for dry straw with 1200 m3/ ha. The highest irrigation water productivity recorded was 1.28 kg m-3, while the rainwater productivity reached 1.73 kg m-3. These results promote agricultural practices resilient to climatic challenges.
