AB  - Marine protected areas (MPAs) play a crucial role in conserving marine biodiversity; however, their effectiveness strongly depends on ecological connectivity within networks. Despite four decades of MPA establishment in China's semi-enclosed Bohai Sea (BS), comprehensive assessments of connectivity remain lacking. This study provides systematic evaluation of ecological connectivity among MPAs in the BS by integrating high-resolution simulations from the Regional Ocean Modeling System (ROMS) with particle-tracking using the OpenDrift framework. Two simulation scenarios were developed: (1) generalized simulations using three pelagic larval durations (PLDs; 1, 7, and 15 days) to explore how PLD influences connectivity; and (2) species-specific simulations for four economically and ecologically significant species (tongue sole, hard clam, razor clam, and Pacific oyster), incorporating distinct spawning behaviors and biological traits. Results identified PLD as a key determinant of network structure. At short PLD, the network was relatively fragmented, with high self-retention (0.47) and limited inter-MPA connectivity. At intermediate PLD, self-retention decreased markedly and regional connectivity increased. At extended PLD, the network became broadly connected with extensive cross-regional links, though complete mixing was not achieved. Species-specific scenarios revealed divergent connectivity patterns shaped by spawning strategy and local hydrodynamics. Tongue sole exhibited moderate dispersal with connections to adjacent MPAs, whereas bottom-spawning razor clam showed exceptionally high self-retention (>49%) within a contained dispersal footprint. Pacific oyster displayed moderate self-retention (10-38%) but remained functionally isolated. These findings underscore the roles of PLD, species traits, and tidal dynamics in shaping connectivity, offering guidance for MPA network optimization in the BS.
