TI  - Detection of ciguatera fish poisoning in the Philippines
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE AND MANAGEMENT
LA  - English
KW  - fish poisoning
KW  - ciguatoxin
KW  - dinoflagellate
KW  - Gambierdiscus
KW  - PACIFIC
AB  - Ciguatera fish poisoning (CFP) is an illness caused by eating fish contaminated with toxins called ciguatoxins (CTX) produced by dinoflagellates, particularly the Gambierdiscus species. People affected by CFP suffer from gastrointestinal and cardiac symptoms, and in some cases, chronic neurologic symptoms. In the Philippines, diagnosis of CFP in humans is based mainly on symptoms caused by recent intake of fish, and confirmation is done with the use of Cigua-Check Kit. Clinical diagnosis alone may not be sufficient because of the observed variability in terms of severity of symptoms, while the Cigua-Check test can be considered as a screening lest for CTX only in fish samples.
   In this study, CFP cases involving 22 individuals from two households in Iloilo province in central Philippines are reported. These individuals experienced range of symptoms common to fish poisoning, while one of them experienced temperature reversal sensation. Cigua-Check Kit screening done by the Bureau of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources indicated the presence of CTX in remnant of fish eaten by the affected individuals. The presence of CTX in blood samples of some affected individuals was confirmed by our group using electrospray ionization mass spectrometry, which showed masses corresponding to those of CTX-1 and CTX-3B/3C. Since an increased occurrence of CFP in the Philippines is anticipated as a consequence of global climate change, validation of CFP by other methods like mass spectrometry will be useful for more effective diagnosis and management of CFP. As far as we know, this is the first report of CFP cases in the Philippines confirmed by mass spectrometry technique.
