AB  - The global decline of chondrichthyan populations underscores the need to better understand species in the French West Indies (FWI) to develop effective, locally adapted conservation measures. This first assessment compiles data from ten years of scientific monitoring and citizen science programs conducted across the FWI. Between 2014 and 2024, a total of 41 chondrichthyan species were documented, including 31 sharks, nine rays, and one chimaera, confirming the FWI as a biodiversity hotspot for this taxonomic group. Of this remarkable diversity, 51.2 % of the recorded species are classified as threatened on the global IUCN Red List, emphasizing their vulnerability. Coastal and oceanic species, with 68.4% and 73.3% respectively listed in the global IUCN Red List, are particularly at risk due to habitat degradation, overfishing, and climate change. The FWI plays a crucial role in the conservation of sharks and rays, providing essential habitats for key life stages. Multiple coastal nurseries have been identified for species such as the Caribbean reef shark (Carcharhinus perezi), the lemon shark (Negaprion brevirostris), and the blacknose shark (Carcharhinus acronotus). Sightings of pregnant females and juveniles of oceanic species, including oceanic whitetip shark (Carcharhinus longimanus), scalloped hammerhead (Sphyrna lewini), and silky shark (Carcharhinus falciformis), further underscore the ecological significance of these waters. It appears essential to continue and prioritize efforts to acquire knowledge across all marine environments, coastal, oceanic, and deep-sea. A better understanding of the biodiversity present in the territorial waters of the FWI is crucial to assess the conservation status of chondrichthyan populations. This involves not only documenting species presence and distribution but also attempting to monitor population trends over time. In addition, particular attention must be paid to the study of interactions between these species and human activities, including both commercial and recreational fisheries, as well as the development of marine tourism. Improved knowledge of these interactions will help identify the most appropriate measures to reduce local pressures, such as bycatch, disturbances, or habitat degradation. The active engagement of local stakeholders, especially fishers and tourism operators, remains critical to the success of conservation initiatives. Their involvement in monitoring, awareness, and management programs will support a better understanding of the issues and promote the adoption of more sustainable practices.
