TI  - Enhancing adaptive capacity through Agro-pastoral innovations in Uganda's drought-prone areas
T2  - AFRICAN GEOGRAPHICAL REVIEW
LA  - English
KW  - Agropastoral system
KW  - adaptive capacity
KW  - droughts
KW  - innovations
KW  - water points
AB  - Drought poses a critical challenge to Agro-pastoral adaptive capacity globally.. While, Agro-pastoralists use innovations to adapt, empirical evidences in Uganda's cattle corridor are limited. This study aimed at assessing how Agro-pastoral innovations enhance adaptive capacity. We used a cross-sectional survey to interview 426 households in six districts to gather insightful data, and statistical analyses including Principal component analysis, Instrumental Variable regression model and student t-test were employedOur findingsrevealedthat agro-pastoral households were proactively responding to the impacts of drought by making strategic innovations in crop varieties, livestock types, fodder, and water harvesting techniques believed strengthen their adaptive capacity. Fodder making emerged as the most preferred innovation among households in central and southwest sub-regions, followed by improved crop and livestock varieties. Additionally, food banking was identified as the most significant innovation for households in the Northeast, underscoring the pivotal role of watering crop and creation of water points for livestock in bolstering adaptive capacity. Fodder making offered feeds, during period of drought and income; accounting for; 43.4%, 43.7%, and 51.2% of the household's total income in the Central, Southwest, and Northeast respectively. In conclusion, our study emphasizes the urgent need to scale up indigenous innovations; water harvesting technologies using both surface and ground tanks, strengtheninglocal fodder production systems and integrating indigenous innovations into national drought adaptation policies taking into consideration the heterogeneities likely to be pervasive in Uganda's cattle corridor.
