TI  - Comparing carbon offsets and livelihood benefits in a long-term reforestation project: Agroforestry versus native timber versus enrichment planting
T2  - ECOLOGICAL SOLUTIONS AND EVIDENCE
LA  - English
KW  - agroforestry
KW  - carbon offset
KW  - community-based reforestation
KW  - fire prevention
KW  - native timber
KW  - natural regrowth
KW  - neotropics
KW  - trade-offs
KW  - RESTORATION
AB  - Indigenous People and Local Communities (IPLC) can play an important role in reforestation for climate change mitigation while providing environmental and livelihood benefits. However, there is a lack of direct comparison between different reforestation design's carbon uptake potential and their relevance to community reforestation. We evaluate the carbon capture and survival of the four most common reforestation designs in a 14-year-long project in an Ember & aacute; community in eastern Panama. We look at native timber mixtures and monocultures, agroforestry, and natural regrowth with enrichment planting. To explain the differences between plots, we compare design, management and environmental characteristics using redundancy analyses (RDA). We then contextualize our results with the project leader's perspectives of success using interviews and workshops. In the first decade, mixtures and monocultures of timber stored on average roughly 3x more carbon than agroforestry and enrichment planting (140 tCO2/ha compared to 40 tCO2/ha and 53 tCO2/ha). The project design had the largest influence on carbon storage and survival with an explanatory power of 31% followed by management and environmental characteristics (14% and 2% respectively). The largest threat to the survival and growth was the risk of fire which caused mortality in more than 2/3 of the plots. Some damage was offset by natural regrowth which accounted for 34% of the total carbon, but the participants generally perceived natural regrowth as being "dirty." They had a strong preference for agroforestry, particularly coffee (Coffea spp.), a crop with negligible carbon value, but high economic value. 'Practical implication': The findings underscore the need to balance carbon sequestration with local economic preferences, integrate community input, mitigate environmental risks and adopt long-term, holistic approaches for effective reforestation projects.
   Los Pueblos Ind & iacute;genas y las Comunidades Locales pueden desempe & ntilde;ar un papel importante en la reforestaci & oacute;n por la mitigaci & oacute;n del cambio clim & aacute;tico que proporciona beneficios ambientales y de sustento de las personas. Sin embargo, hace falta una comparaci & oacute;n directa entre el potencial de captura de carbono de diferentes dise & ntilde;os de reforestaci & oacute;n y su relevancia para la reforestaci & oacute;n comunitaria. Evaluamos la captura de carbono y la supervivencia de los cuatro dise & ntilde;os de reforestaci & oacute;n m & aacute;s comunes en un proyecto de 14 a & ntilde;os que se lleva a cabo en una comunidad Ember & aacute; en el este de Panam & aacute;. Evaluamos plantaciones con mezclas y monocultivos de madera nativa, agroforester & iacute;a y sistemas de regeneraci & oacute;n natural con plantaci & oacute;n de enriquecimiento. Para explicar las diferencias entre parcelas, comparamos el dise & ntilde;o, la gesti & oacute;n y las caracter & iacute;sticas medioambientales mediante an & aacute;lisis de redundancia. A continuaci & oacute;n, contextualizamos nuestros resultados con la perspectiva de los l & iacute;deres del proyecto de su & eacute;xito mediante entrevistas y talleres. En la primera d & eacute;cada, las mezclas y los monocultivos de madera almacenaron en promedio aproximadamente 3 veces m & aacute;s carbono que la agroforester & iacute;a y la plantaci & oacute;n de enriquecimiento (140 tCO2/ha en comparaci & oacute;n con 40 tCO2/ha y 53 tCO2/ha). El dise & ntilde;o del proyecto tuvo la mayor influencia en el almacenamiento de carbono y la supervivencia, con un poder explicativo del 31%, seguido por la gesti & oacute;n y las caracter & iacute;sticas ambientales (14% y 2% respectivamente). La mayor amenaza para la supervivencia y el crecimiento fue el riesgo de incendio, que caus & oacute; mortalidad en m & aacute;s de 2/3 de las parcelas. Algunos da & ntilde;os fueron compensados por el crecimiento natural, que represent & oacute; el 34% del carbono total, pero los participantes generalmente percibieron el crecimiento natural como "sucio." Hay una fuerte preferencia por la agroforester & iacute;a, especialmente el caf & eacute; (Coffea spp.), un cultivo con un valour de carbono insignificante, pero de alto valour econ & oacute;mico. 'Implicaciones pr & aacute;cticas': Las conclusiones resaltan la necesidad de equilibrar la captura de carbono con las preferencias econ & oacute;micas locales, integrar la participaci & oacute;n de la comunidad, mitigar los riesgos ambientales y adoptar enfoques hol & iacute;sticos y a largo plazo para proyectos de reforestaci & oacute;n efectivos.
   Looking at different reforestation methods over 14 years in an Ember & aacute; Indigenous community in Panama we found that plots with native timber mixtures and monocultures stored three times more carbon than those with agroforestry or natural regrowth. Natural regrowth was less valued by participants due to the abundance of pioneer species, but it helped mitigate impacts from fires, which threatened over two-thirds of the plots. Agroforestry, especially with high-value crops like coffee, offered significant economic benefits despite lower carbon storage.image
